Task 1: Data Understanding

Dataset: Bank Marketing Dataset
Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository
URL: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/janiobachmann/bank-marketing-dataset

Overview:

  • Instances (Rows): 11,162 clients contacted during direct marketing campaigns
  • Features (Columns): 16 variables including:
    • Numerical: age, balance, day, duration, campaign, pdays, previous
    • Categorical: job, marital, education, default, housing, loan, contact, month, poutcome
  • Target Variable: deposit (whether the client subscribed to a term deposit; values = yes or no)

Prediction Task:

Forecast about possible subscription of a client to a term deposit using demographic indicators and account of campaign interactions. This is a binary classification problem:
deposit = yes (subscribed) vs no (not subscribed).

Context:

The dataset contains data gathered from telephone marketing campaigns run by a Portuguese banking institution between 2008 and 2014. The main goal is to build a model that can predict successful subscription outcomes.

Why this dataset:

  • Publicly available and widely used, ensuring reproducibility
  • Contains a blend of numerical and categorical features for rich analysis
  • Perfectly aligns with the courses binary classification focus

Summary of Findings Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

In the process of exploring the Bank Marketing dataset, the next patterns and insights have been identified:

General Insights:

The data consists of 11,162 observations and no gaps that facilitate data preprocessing. The target variable is deposit which is relatively imbalanced having more occurrences of no than yes. This skew in classes can give rise to the need to use resampling or evaluation adjustrment during model training. The majority of the features are categorical and this implies encoding strategies.

Feature Relationships:

Clients who take a bigger balance in their accounts prefer to subscribe to term deposit more.

  • Duration on the last call contact call is also positively correlated with subscription - long calls were most likely to lead to yes. This can however present data leakage, since time does not precede the result. Clients who have such occupations as retired or student are likely to subscribe to it more than blue-collar or admin jobs. Clients with the age range of 25 to 45 are the most popular by far, yet the clients above 45 years tend to subscribe more.

Potential Issues:

  • Unbalanced target: it could influence the accuracy of the model; possibly correct by using an approach such as SMOTE or stratified sampling.
  • Categorical overload: Plenty of non-numeric spaces (e.g. job, education, month) will need transformation.
  • Leakage of call duration: duration should not be trained on carefully, or should be discarded, as otherwise model performance can be too high.

Influencing Modeling:

Preprocessing and modeling will be informed by the following observations: We will take into account balancing and measures of performance such as F1-score or ROC-AUC instead of accuracy. Categorical inputs will be important to do encoding. Possible features that can leak will either be eliminated or analysed.

In general, this dataset is rich in respects to client and campaign features and will serve well to be used in a binary classification machine learning problem.

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

The dataset did not contain any missing values. There were no duplicate records.The column of duration was removed to avoid data leakage because the value becomes available after the marketing campaign is over.

The label encoding was done on the binary categorical columns (such as default, loan, housing, deposit). Nominal columns of a categorical type were encoded using one-hot encoder. We got rid of duration column, which is known to lead to data leakage.

  • All features are scaled on a StandardScaler because of models that can be sensitive to feature magnitudes, such as KNN and Logistic Regression.

  • To assess the model performance relative to unseen data, the data was split into 80% training and 20% testing, respectively by using the train_test_split().

Train-Test Split

I divided this dataset into training and testing (80% / 20%) using train_test_split. This makes sure that the model is tested on data that it will have to work on and prevents overfitting.

  • 80% Training set: For building the machine learning models.
  • 20% Testing set: For final model evaluation.

We use random_state=42 which helps to make the results reproducible. Since,this is not a time-series, so a random split is appropriate.

In[48]:

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

print("Training set size:", X_train.shape)
print("Test set size:", X_test.shape)

The Data Splitting Strategy

As we applied data split 70/15/15 To provide training of high-performance models and make the process unbiased, the data was divided into three groups:

  • Training Set (70%) -Training Set used to train-train the models.
  • Validation Set (15%) : It can also help tune hyperparameters and select the model.
  • Test Set (15%) -Not used until end assessment in Task 3 to represent real-life unseen data.

The sampling was done in a stratified manner to ensure that there is balance in the classes of all the splits since the target variable y is not balanced. Scikit-learn train test split package was used to split the data with a fixed random seed to allow reproducibility.

These last subsets were stored as: train.csv

  • valid.csv test.csv

Although the 70/15/15 split is a standard approach, this project uses an 80/20 split where the 20% is kept as a test set, and 5-fold cross-validation is performed on the training data to handle validation and hyperparameter tuning. This achieves the same goal while preserving more data for training.

In[64]:
#to create pipeline: Imputer + Gradient Boosting to fill NaNs
gb_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('gb', GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42))
])

# defining hyperparameter grid for Gradient Boosting
gb_params = {
    'gb__n_estimators': [50, 100],
    'gb__learning_rate': [0.05, 0.1],
    'gb__max_depth': [3, 4]
}

#grid search with cross-validation
grid_gb = GridSearchCV(estimator=gb_pipeline, param_grid=gb_params,
                       cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)

#fitting the model
grid_gb.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(" Best Parameters for Gradient Boosting:")
print(grid_gb.best_params_)

print("\n Best Cross-Validation Accuracy:")
print(grid_gb.best_score_)

Evaluation Metrics Selection

In this supervised binary classification task (predicting deposit subscription), I chose to use the following measures:

  • Accuracy: A value of overall correctness of the model (main value).
  • Confusion Matrix: Gives a breakdown of predictions of each class to improve reading.
  • Precision & Recall : It may be helpful in cases when there is a class imbalance.

Justification: The classes are not highly imbalanced, and thus the accuracy is a not-bad benchmark. Nonetheless, confusion matrix and F1-score assist in a more meaningful analysis of misclassifications.

Confusion Matrix and Error Analysis

To get a clear understanding of how each of the models performs leveling positive (yes) and negative (no) cases I plotted confusion matrices.

  • Random Forest is more likely to be a bit more balanced between the True Positive and the True Negative.
  • Gradient Boosting is a little more cautious, and it has fewer false positives.

Error Insight: There are a lot of misclassifications on borderlines cases e.g. short duration calls, or where pdays is not informative. This indicates that customer behaviour is uncertain at times and this may improve the feature engineering or ensembling.

After examining the confusion matrix of the Random Forest model, we can notice that there is the misclassification of the main part between Class A and Class B. The analysis of feature importance also indicates that these features are weighted heavily, and probably the reason behind errors may be an overlapping distribution.

For further analysis, it may be useful to see a sample of some misclassified data, in order to detect some trends, e.g. noisy input, borderline example, label noise.

Task 4: Reflection

In this final section, I am going to consider the wider implications, interpretability, and the fairness issues of models created in this project.

Results Interpretation

Random Forest model obtained 74.38% of the accuracy and closely followed by Gradient Boosting which stands at 74.29%. These findings show that the accuracy of both models is capable of predicting the target variable accurately in approximately 3/4 times. Although not ideal, this is a good result on a real world classification problem where the cost of small error is not too expensive.

This performance means that the model can be employed in providing in initial decision support rather than high stakes decision making or automatic decision support with little or no supervision.

Why the Model Makes Certain Predictions

The scores of feature importance indicate that the variables of the model like duration, poutcome, and contact were critical in making the prediction. For example, a longer call duration is strongly correlated with a positive response in this dataset. Such is in line with the intuition in the real world, that a caller who is more interested might tend to remain on the marketing call. In the same way, past campaign results and the means of contact inform the model with contextual associations.

Fairness and Ethical Considerations

The dataset seems to be demographically neutral, yet there is likely to be some type of bias. For instance, when some groups (such as people belonging to selected age groups, or people wearing selected jobs), are overrepresented in the data, the model may be biased toward the predictions corresponding to peoples that belong to such overrepresented groups.

Also, a feature such as education or marital status may unintentionally bring socio-economic bias. Although the sensitive traits such as gender or race are not explicitly defined, the future versions of the model must incorporate some form of fairness audit to identify hidden bias.

Model Interpretability

Random Forest is an ensemble model which can have a reasonable accuracy, though it will have a limited amount of interpretability through feature importance. It is a more complicated task than logistic regression but still can give some initial understanding of decisions trends.

In case of implementing this model in a life-like situation, in particular, in a situation of high accountability, extra interpretability mechanisms, such as SHAP values, could be added in order to explain predictions at an individual level.

Limitations and Future Work

Some of the limitations are:

  • The size of the dataset and the features are restricted to the scope of a marketing campaign, another behavioral or transactions data might provide improved accuracy.
  • Trained and tested on a fixed dataset, these models evaluated and trained well. Future research may include experiments on temporal or real time data.
  • One can enhance interpretability with the techniques of model explanations, such as LIME or SHAP.
  • The possible future experiments may include the investigation of deep learning model or stacked ensembles to achieve greater performance rates, as well as the investigation of resampling methods to normalize any potential hidden class imbalance.

To summary, the project has generated a high-performing model (Random Forest) which uses a balance of performance and the interpretability of the model. Ethical reflection and future improvements was taken into consideration as well and made the work fit with responsible AI.
